    "body": "```python\r\ndef foo():\r\n    cdef char cstr[256]\r\n    c_get_name(cstr)\r\n    name = cstr\r\n    c_get_address(cstr)\r\n    address = cstr\r\n    return name == address\r\n```\r\n\r\n`foo` always returns `True` no matter what is copied to `cstr` by `c_get_name` and `c_get_address`.\r\n\r\nCheck the generated C code and see `cstr` is just assigned to other `char *` variables instead of calling `PyString_FromString` immediately like pyrex.\r\n\r\nCython calls `PyString_FromString` at a later time for both the `char *` variables, since they just point to the same variable `cstr`, `name == address` is always `True`.\r\n\r\nThis issue is seen in 0.25.2",
    "closed_at": "2017-06-19T22:46:46Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "body": "This is due to type inference. Here `name` and `address` are inferred to be of type `char*`. If you want them to be objects, write `name = <object>cstr` or `name = str(cstr)` or `cdef object name = cstr` or simply disable inference with a compiler directive. ",
